<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n11034j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n11" href="#n11034j">N11 (VI.B.5)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n11all.htm#n11034j"> 34(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> syllepsis</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">(qu&apos;est-ce qu&apos;une &ldquo;incorrection&rdquo;? il n&apos;en est gu&egrave;re qu&apos;on ne p&ucirc;t justifier par un exemple tir&eacute; de Littr&eacute; ou par les mots d&apos;anacoluthe et de <mark>syllepse</mark>) <small> Jacques Boulenger et Andr&eacute; Th&eacute;rive, <a name="JBAT" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JBAT"><cite title="source">Les Soir&eacute;es du Grammaire-Club</cite></a> (1924) 41</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Syllepsis. 1. A rhetorical figure by which a word agrees syntactically with two or more other words in the same sentence, but has a different sense in relation to each. E.g. &lsquo;Here thou, great Anna! whom three realms obey, / Dost sometimes counsel take &mdash; and sometimes tea.&rsquo; (Pope&apos;s <i>The Rape of the Lock</i>, III, 7.) 2. The use of a word to refer to two or more words in the same sentence, while qualifying only one of them grammatically. For example, a masculine adjective applied to masculine and feminine substantives. </mm> </dd></dl>
